text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LanguageOfTheNacirema]]%0a%0a!Philosophy lessons from CHAIR%0a%0a:Author: abbyl%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aPolysemy of "chair"%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aYou can be the CHAIR of a committee and be referred to as the CHAIRMAN while you are CHAIRING the committee. You can sit in a CHAIR and play armCHAIR therapist for your friends even if you're not an actual therapist. You can make children like you if you play musical-CHAIRS with them. You can go skiing and ride a CHAIRlift during your trip. You could even become a professor and hold a CHAIR in your field of specialty. You can audition for first-CHAIR of an orchestra for your instrument. Or you can audition for second-CHAIR. You can build railroad CHAIRS. If you are particularly well-liked, you can even get your friends to CHAIR you around a room.%0a%0aNacirema culture seems to be focused on both leisure or status. For example, playing armchair therapist has the connotation of doing it as a hobby and not really having much expertise in the area. Similarly, sitting in a chair implies relaxation and musical chairs is a popular game. On the other hand, positions referred to as a chair usually imply a status of either achievement or leadership. Nacirema cultures seems to represent any desirable status as a chair, maybe because physical chairs are study and dependable. %0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210319-235231-260520#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!The Etymology of Chair %0a-> - AlexisA%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aThe noun chair, as in the place where one sits, comes from the old French word, chaëre, meaning chair, seat, or throne. The verb chair (to install in a chair of authority) comes directly from the noun form and chair as in a position of authority seems to have the same origin. The use of chaëre to mean throne puts into context the English form meaning "to chair a committee," since thrones imply a position of power. Thus, it seems unlikely that the use of the same word for the two major meanings of the English chair implies that English speakers perceive a relationship between the two concepts.%0a%0aSources:%0ahttps://www.oed.com/search?searchType=dictionary&q=chair&_searchBtn=Search%0ahttps://www.etymonline.com/word/chair#etymonline_v_44622 (my former Latin teacher's favorite etymology website)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210319-235231-260520#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: B:)%0a(:Category: LanguageOfTheNacirema:)%0a(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LanguageOfTheNacirema]]%0a%0a!Philosophy Lessons from CHAIR%0a%0a:Author: rajeev_g%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aIllustrating the polysemy of "chair"%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aLet us consider the Nacirema's use of the word CHAIR. I can sit down in a CHAIR, but the CHAIRwoman of the committee might be standing. The first CHAIR viola might be CHAIRing a meeting for a treasonous plot, which gets him sent to the CHAIR.%0a%0aThe Nacirema live greatly sedentary lifestyles, and believe in strong structures of hierarchy. As such, they worship the chair, as the center of their daily routines. They also believe that every group requires a leader (whose authority is derived from the holy chair). The Nacirema tend to enforce strict political and social hierarchy.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: A:)%0a(:Category: LanguageOfTheNacirema:)
