 comes directly from the noun form and chair as in a position of authority seems to have the same origin. The use of chaëre to mean throne puts into context the English form meaning "to chair a committee," since thrones imply a position of power. Thus, it seems unlikely that the use of the same word for the two major meanings of the English chair implies that English speakers perceive a relationship between the two concepts.%0a> %0a> Sources:%0a> https://www.oed.com/search?searchType=dictionary&q=chair&_searchBtn=Search%0a
