diff:1616197951:1616195922:=48,60c48%0a%3c #foxbegin 210319-235231-260520#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!The Etymology of Chair %0a%3c -> - AlexisA%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c The noun chair, as in the place where one sits, comes from the old French word, chaëre, meaning chair, seat, or throne. The verb chair (to install in a chair of authority) comes directly from the noun form and chair as in a position of authority seems to have the same origin. The use of chaëre to mean throne puts into context the English form meaning "to chair a committee," since thrones imply a position of power. Thus, it seems unlikely that the use of the same word for the two major meanings of the English chair implies that English speakers perceive a relationship between the two concepts.%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c https://www.oed.com/search?searchType=dictionary&q=chair&_searchBtn=Search%0a%3c https://www.etymonline.com/word/chair#etymonline_v_44622 (my former Latin teacher's favorite etymology website)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210319-235231-260520#%0a---%0a> %0a
